					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-10815154#post-4199091</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-10815154/scp-4233#post-4199091</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Wed, 27 Mar 2019 23:33:54 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>not_a_seagull</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>3009022</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <blockquote> <p>Once on land, SCP-4233 will continue walking at a gradual pace (slightly less than 5 kilometers per hour) in a straight line, only altering its trajectory to avoid injuring civilians, animals, and large plants such as trees.</p> </blockquote> <p>You could contain him pretty easily by surrounding him with a ring of D-class. If he avoids injuring people, he'll probably just stay still.</p> <p>I like this one. There's a BioShock-esque feel here, and I quite like that. It also proposes a lot of questions. What, exactly, is his relation to <a href="http://www.scpwiki.com/scp-1233">SCP-1233</a>? Do they have a common origin? Are there any other &quot;champions&quot; out there that the Foundation doesn't know about? Are any other anomalies secretly &quot;champions?&quot; The implications here are quite good.</p> <p>My main complaint is that it feels like there's something missing in the dialogue. I can't put my finger on it, but when I go back and read 1233, and then I read this, I feel like there's something wrong.</p> <p>In any case, this is great. +1</p> 
